		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">James Ellroy</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<table class="infobox vcard vevent" style="width:22em; font-size:90%; text-align:left;">
<tr>
<th colspan="2" style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" class="fn summary">James Ellroy</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>Born</th>
<td>March 4, 1948 <span style="display:none">(<span class="bday">1948-03-04</span>)</span> <span class="noprint">(age&#160;61)</span><br />
<a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles,_California" title="Los Angeles, California" class="mw-redirect">Los Angeles, California</a>,<br />
<a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><a href="/wiki/Employment" title="Employment">Occupation</a></th>
<td><a href="/wiki/Novel" title="Novel">Novelist</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><a href="/wiki/Nationality" title="Nationality">Nationality</a></th>
<td><a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>James Ellroy</b> (born <b>Lee Earle Ellroy</b> <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1948-03-04"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="03-04"><a href="/wiki/March_4" title="March 4">March 4</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1948" title="1948">1948</a></span>) is an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Crime_writer" title="Crime writer">crime writer</a> and <a href="/wiki/Essayist" title="Essayist" class="mw-redirect">essayist</a>.</p>
<p>Ellroy has become a pioneer of the so-called '<a href="/wiki/Telegraph" title="Telegraph" class="mw-redirect">telegraphic</a>' <a href="/wiki/Prose_style" title="Prose style" class="mw-redirect">prose style</a>, whereby he frequently omits connecting words and uses only short, <a href="/wiki/Staccato" title="Staccato">staccato</a> sentences<sup id="cite_ref-Miller_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Miller-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>. For instance: "They sent him to Dallas to kill a nigger pimp named Wendell Durfee. He wasn't sure he could do it. The Casino Operators Council flew him. They supplied first-class fare. They tapped their slush fund. They greased him. They fed him six cold."<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Other hallmarks of his work include dense plotting and a relentlessly <a href="/wiki/Pessimistic" title="Pessimistic" class="mw-redirect">pessimistic</a> — albeit conservatively moral — worldview.<sup id="cite_ref-Salon_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Salon-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Onion_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Onion-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> For this, Ellroy has been nicknamed the "Demon Dog of American crime fiction."<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
